# Go guidelines

Follow [Effective Go](https://go.dev/doc/effective_go) and [Go Code Review Comments](https://github.com/golang/go/wiki/CodeReviewComments). Use `gofmt` / `goimports`. Treat `golangci-lint` warnings as errors; avoid `//nolint` without a comment explaining why.

## ELVish-specific patterns

For mail packages (`internal/mail*`, `internal/scyllastore`, `internal/blobstore`), also follow **[mail-subsystem.mdc](.cursor/rules/mail-subsystem.mdc)** — the four-store architecture and security invariants apply.

For SMTP code (`internal/smtp*`, `internal/dkim`), see **[smtp-dkim.mdc](.cursor/rules/smtp-dkim.mdc)**.

**Naming:** `camelCase` unexported, `PascalCase` exported. Acronyms: `userID`, `httpClient`, `URLPath`. Packages: lowercase single word (`store`, not `stores` or `data_store`). Receivers: 1–2 letters from type (`s *Server`). Avoid named returns except in very short functions where they document clearly.

## Errors

Never ignore errors; `_ = fn()` only with a comment when truly irrelevant. Wrap with `fmt.Errorf("context: %w", err)`. Use `errors.Is` / `errors.As` — never string-match `err.Error()`. Sentinel errors for checkable cases; structured types for domain errors. No `panic` for recoverable errors; no `panic` in libraries. Error strings: lowercase, no trailing punctuation.

## Layout

Prefer `cmd/`, `internal/`, `pkg/` sparingly. `cmd/<app>/main.go` wires only; business logic in `internal/`. No `util` / `helpers` / `common` / `misc` packages.

## Interfaces

Define interfaces where they are **used**, not where implemented. Small interfaces (often 1–3 methods). No preemptive interfaces. Accept interfaces, return concrete types. Do not embed an interface in a struct to fake implementation.

## Concurrency

Every goroutine stoppable; use `context.Context` for cancellation. `ctx` first param on I/O / wait / spawn. Never store `Context` in a struct. `sync.WaitGroup` for joins; not `time.Sleep` for sync. Channels for signaling; mutexes for shared state. Use `errgroup` for fan-out with errors. CI: `go test -race`.

## Functions

One responsibility; ~50 lines max; ~5 params max (group in structs). Functional options for many optionals. Avoid boolean parameters — use enums/types. Consistent pointer receivers on a type. Avoid naked `return` in longer functions.

## Types

Illegal states unrepresentable. Newtypes for domain IDs. `iota` enums with meaningful zero. Minimal embedding. Unexported fields by default. Prefer generics or typed interfaces over `any` / frequent assertions.

## Generics

Use when multiple types share identical logic; tight constraints; avoid generic public APIs unless necessary.

## Modules

Prefer stdlib; audit deps. Commit `go.sum`. `go mod tidy` before commit. `govulncheck` in CI. Cautious with `replace` in published libraries.

## Testing

Tests for exported symbols; table-driven tests. Names: `TestFunctionName_Scenario_ExpectedOutcome`. `t.Helper()` in helpers. Prefer fakes over heavy mocks; minimal interfaces in `_test.go` when mocking. `t.Parallel()` when safe. `testify/require` vs `assert` appropriately. `httptest` for HTTP — not real servers in unit tests.

## Docs

Doc comments on all exported identifiers; start with the name: `// Server handles ...`. Explain why/when. `Example` functions in `_test.go` for non-trivial exports.

## Logging

Structured logging (`log/slog`, zap, zerolog). No logging inside libraries — return errors. Correct levels; correlate with context (trace/request metadata).

## HTTP

Stdlib or thin router first. Set `ReadTimeout`, `WriteTimeout`, `IdleTimeout` on `http.Server`. Composable `func(http.Handler) http.Handler` middleware. `http.MaxBytesReader` on bodies. Structured JSON errors; no internal details in responses. `defer r.Body.Close()`. Validate at the boundary.

## CI (merge gate)

`go fmt`, `go vet`, `golangci-lint`, `go test -race ./...`, benchmarks job, `govulncheck ./...`.

```go
// ❌ BAD — ignored error
_, _ = io.ReadAll(r.Body)

// ✅ GOOD
data, err := io.ReadAll(r.Body)
if err != nil {
    return fmt.Errorf("read body: %w", err)
}
```

## Security (mail and auth code)

- Never log secrets, private keys, plaintext mail bodies, or session tokens
- Use generic messages for auth failures ("Invalid credentials")
- Validate sizes and shapes at HTTP boundaries (`http.MaxBytesReader`)
- Time-constant comparisons for tokens and proofs

See [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) for the full "Browser UI security" and conventions sections.
